  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n- Limited international cooperation\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) establishment in 1989\n- Introduced international standards and recommendations\n- Promoted global anti-money laundering (AML) strategies\n\n3. Major Legislative Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased financial institution responsibilities\n- Stricter customer identification protocols\n\n4. International Collaboration\n- United Nations conventions\n- Enhanced cross-border information sharing\n- Standardized regulatory frameworks\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Beneficial ownership transparency requirements\n- Expanded definitions of financial crimes\n\n6. Technological Adaptations\n- Advanced data analytics\n- Machine learning for transaction tracking\n- Real-time monitoring systems\n- Artificial intelligence for risk assessment\n\n7. Current Focus\n- Combating terrorist financing\n- Addressing emerging financial technologies\n- Strengthening international enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve, addressing increasingly sophisticated financial crime techniques.",
